Crime During the Pandemic

John D. Harden

2020-09-01

How The Washington Post Analyzed Crime

The Washington Post began collecting crime data from several cities across the country in beginning in mid-March. Early on during the pandemic – it was reported that crime had dropped in several cities when stay-at-home orders were enacted. However, the Post set out to analysis new patterns in crime that may have emerged under the umbrella of the pandemic.

The Post selected 27 cities to created an aggregated rate of major crimes which includes rape, robbery, homicide, burglary, auto theft and theft from vehicle. Data shows an overall drop in crime in March through early April. Those 27 cities collectively saw the rate of crimes occurring every 21 days drop from XX to XX.

That changed in May – a period marked by the death of George Floyd, which criminal experts say may or may not be related to recent crimes patterns.

But since then – crime grew.

The data was collected via open web portals from each respective city. The data was then cleaned and standardized using R and UCR definitions for violent and property crimes. More than 800,000 reported crimes were collected from 2020. An additional XX million crimes were collected for years 2018 and 2019 to compare current crime trends.

The overall rate was created by dividing all crimes by combined population of each city. The rates for majority Asian, Black, Latino and White neighborhoods were created totaling the populations of each Census tract with a majority racial group present and then dividing crimes by the extracted total population figures.

Granular Crime Rates: Crime in neighborhoods of color

Crime models revealed a disparity between majority Black and majority White neighborhoods – particularly violent crime. A Washington Post analysis of crime data showed that the disparity grew by 65 percent during the pandemic.

Limitations of data

The data is based on data collected from open data portals from respective cities. Police departments from each city … In a few cities, the longitude or latitudes are suppressed for some crimes that include rape and sexual assault and pending homicide investigations. Police departments suggest indpendent verification of crimes for complete accuracy of the reporting process.
